column132: I would begin by acknowledging the faculty member's significant contributions to the university and their esteemed reputation in the academic community. This sets a positive tone for the negotiation and emphasizes their worth to the institution. Also I'd highlight the university's commitment to academic integrity and scientific advancement over profit-driven motives. I'd express concerns about setting precedents that might compromise these values and the university's reputation. I'd acknowledge the faculty member's well-earned sabbatical request and express willingness to accommodate their need for a break. I would also emphasize the importance of work-life balance and the value of providing scholars with the freedom to pursue their research interests. I would propose a buy-out offer for a portion of the faculty member's patent interests that aligns with the $275,000 limit set by the IP Committee. This offer demonstrates the university's commitment to supporting their intellectual property endeavors while ensuring responsible financial management. Throughout the negotiation, I'd remain firm on the $275,000 limit for the patent buy-out and the university's policies regarding sabbatical duration. Next, I'd reinforce the consequences of exceeding these boundaries while emphasizing the university's desire to retain the faculty member.

column132:
I plan to start with an opening bid of 400,000. I will mention that I am interested in taking a sabbatical and due to its length, do not expect to remain paid by the university, as other universities have offered their top scholars. To financially support myself, I would offer to sell my patent portfolio, which contains significantly useful patents in my field, to the university for $400,000 USD. This is reasonable, as a colleague at this same university sold his portfolio to a private company for the same price, though his patents were far less useful than mine. 

I believe in the importance of science and academia, which is why I would prefer to sell my portfolio to the university. However, if the university refuses my offer, I am not unopposed to selling my portfolio to a private company, which would not only offer a higher payment but better wages. The university should be aware that I am one of the top scholars in the world for this field, but after years of hard work, I am getting burnt out. I want to stay creatively viable and for that, need to take this break so I can return with energy to continue my work. If this is not made available for me, the working conditions at this university will not allow me to work here any further, and I will pursue the many offers that I have from other top-tier universities.

column132: I plan on trying to hide as much information as possible with only certain exceptions. I'm going to heavily emphasize that I have been working really hard and I was medically told that I need time off and I discussed with my doctor doing a 21-month sabbatical and that it is a non-negotiable. I also will emphasize my reputation of being a rising star and that I have many options with private investors that will get me a highly rewarded deal if I go with them. I'm going to start strong and high ball at around $500k in hopes that after negotiating, it will guarantee I get my target price of $355k, but I won't be the first to throw out a number as I want to have the control of the situation. My best alternative is to make a deal with a private company; however, I don't want to strongly consider that as I would not meet many of my goals like getting the sabbatical, securing the down payment, and getting the money on a swift timeline.

column106: The sabbatical term will be 12 months, and the grand total of the patent portfolio will be $260,000. The university will provide housing and dining upon the scientist's return.
column132: I plan to offer a lower salary each month for the scientist's sabbatical months and offer to provide more each time when resistance comes. Since I cannot pay more than $275,000 for the star scientst's

column106: While I was unable to reach a deal of $350,000, I was offered an apartment upon arrival and a dining plan on top of the $260,000 for the portfolio, so it makes up for a good portion of the money lost since I will not have to pay rent. In addition, I will be paid for 6 months, so total that is $320,000 total earned from the university. I will reach out and stay in contact with the provost for ideas on how to earn $30,000 more dollars, though I do feel it is possible through research or other work.
column132:
I want to go slightly under $355,000, as $350,000 feels more even of a number and less complicated of a number, since it's halfway between $300,000 and $400,000. I can raise $5,000 myself, as I am a star scientist and can probably get employed for a short amount of time to supplement my salary.
In the negotiation, I will emphasize the necessity of my break to my research/work's success. If I am burnt out and truly cannot perform well, then there is no way I will be helpful to the university. In addition, having more time to think about new ideas will allow them to come to fruition. 
To make this possible, I will be honest and start with the same opening and target price.

column106: 10k return fund, 20k towards additional expenses, 60k sabbatical pay; temporary housing on campus for 3 months, part-time for 3 months at regular salary for me to settle back in, mental health resources if needed
column132: I'm going to introduce myself, ask first how much they're willing to give, if it's above my target price, I would just go with it. If below, I'll ask them how they came to their numbers, ask if there's things they're wiling to provide me so that it's not going to part of my target price.

column106: I offered $25,000 for expenses related to her vacation, $10,000 for her return fund, mental health services at the behavioral health center at the university, free lodging on campus in one of the unused dorms for 3 months, and a part-time schedule at full salary for 3 months to help her reacclimate. I realized quickly that I misspoke and went over my budget with $280,000, so I'm probably going to get fired.
column132: My strategy is to appeal to their sense of loyalty by portraying myself as a friend and colleague, and not as a roadblock to money or benefits.

column132: My opening bid will be 150,000. I am prepared to increase in increments of 25,000, and I hope to be able to land around 225,000. I will tell the scientist that the absolute maximum I can give them is 250,000. After this, I will discuss alternative incentives to staying, such as support for a next patent project or permission for the scientist to work on a project of their choosing after return of their sabbatical. I can also offer to extend the sabbatical, though it will have to be unpaid past 6 months. If, and only if, it is necessary to retain the scientist, I will then offer 275,000.
